<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Yes we fleshed this idea out awhile back</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?TheBlack[BCK]">TheBlack[BCK]</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 2:21 p.m. 10/3/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Yes we fleshed this idea out awhile back<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=1325" TARGET=_self>I posted about this subject a long time ago....</A> (Min)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>

<BR>The solution I proposed then was this:
<P>If 5 level 10's wish to attack a level 16, as soon as the first initiates an attack the attacked player receives a notification message with accompanying sound. The level 10 is then unable to actually begin the attack for a short delay period, say three seconds. As additional members of this band of level 10's attacks the 16, they too trigger the message and have a short delay imposed before the 16 becomes attackable to them and vice versa. This gives the 16 enough time to react and prevents scenario's where a large gang of lower level players completely surrounds a higher level before commencing to beat upon that person. The lower levels do not gain an advantage by attacking out of their range. The three second delay is just a suggestion and could be tweaked through game play to arrive at a good value.
<P>&gt; There is a big difference between being able to initiate combat
<BR>&gt; and being able to defend yourself. Let's take this lv 16 guy in
<BR>&gt; the previous post for example, if he can only wait until the 5
<BR>&gt; lv 10 players attack him before he can initiate combat, it puts
<BR>&gt; a horrible disadvantage on him. It basicly means those 5 lv 10
<BR>&gt; players can just tag along and wait for the best time and place
<BR>&gt; to attack this lv 16, and the lv 16 won't be able to do anything
<BR>&gt; to chase them away. It also gives every lv 10 a free spell
<BR>&gt; attack in the beginning, spells that the lv 16 cannot interrupt
<BR>&gt; because he can't initiate anything offensive against those lv
<BR>&gt; 10.
<P>&gt; If 2 people are allowed to fight each other, let them both be
<BR>&gt; able to initiate combat the way they see fit.
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
